From: ConsoleRDP <consolerdp@local>
Date: Mon, 4 May 2026 08:20:00 -0500
Subject: Fix libx264 encoder color pipeline for mstsc compatibility

Three related fixes bundled together because they all live in the
same function and one depends on the other:

1. Initialization-order bug in LibX264Encoder ctor
--------------------------------------------------
The ctor built m_filterGraphToParse from m_colorRange, but at ctor
time m_colorRange is still the Encoder base-class default (Limited).
PipeWireProduce::setupEncoder() calls encoder->setColorRange(...)
*after* the encoder is constructed and *before* encoder->initialize()
runs -- but the filter string was already baked. Result: setting
ColorRange::Full on the stream silently did nothing; the filter kept
squeezing YUV into 16-235 while the H.264 VUI advertised Full range.
mstsc saw "Full" in the VUI, passed the Y values through verbatim,
and rendered 16-235 as if it were 0-255 -> lifted blacks (pure black
displays as ~#262626 on mstsc).

Fix: move the filter-graph string construction from the ctor to
initialize(), which runs AFTER setColorRange(). The ctor is now a
no-op for color setup.

2. Force BT.601 color matrix in the scale filter
------------------------------------------------
mstsc / the RDP-EGFX reference decoder uses BT.601 YUV->RGB math
regardless of what the H.264 VUI says. The stock libswscale default
for >= 720p is BT.709, which produces a mismatched inverse on the
mstsc side (subtly off reds/greens). Force the output matrix to
BT.601 so encoder and decoder agree.

3. Write explicit BT.601 VUI metadata
-------------------------------------
Without setting color_primaries / color_trc / colorspace on the
AVCodecContext, libx264 writes color_description_present_flag=0
and decoders guess. Be explicit: all three set to SMPTE170M
(BT.601 525-line, which is what RDP-EGFX is specified against).
color_range is tied to m_colorRange so the VUI and the filter
agree bit-for-bit.

Also adds two one-shot qCWarning log markers
(CONSOLERDP-LIBX264-FILTER-GRAPH and CONSOLERDP-BT601-VUI-PATCH-ACTIVE)
so a live session can confirm at runtime that the patched path fired.

Tested with mstsc 10.0.x on Windows 11 -> KRdp via Hyper-V VMConnect
capture vs mstsc capture. Before: #000 on host shown as ~#262426 in
mstsc. After: #000 on host shown as #000 in mstsc.

---
 src/libx264encoder.cpp | 30 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++----
 1 file changed, 26 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

--- a/src/libx264encoder.cpp
+++ b/src/libx264encoder.cpp
@@ -32,16 +32,21 @@ LibX264Encoder::LibX264Encoder(H264Profile profile, PipeWireProduce *produce)
     : SoftwareEncoder(produce)
     , m_profile(profile)
 {
-    auto colorRange = m_colorRange == PipeWireBaseEncodedStream::ColorRange::Full ? u"full"_s : u"limited"_s;
-
-    // Adjust the filter graph to ensure we are using an even frame size using a
-    // pad filter. Otherwise the size adjustment below will insert a row/column
-    // of garbage instead of black.
-    m_filterGraphToParse = u"format=yuv420p,pad=ceil(iw/2)*2:ceil(ih/2)*2,scale=out_range=%1"_s.arg(colorRange);
+    // Note: do NOT build m_filterGraphToParse here. At this point
+    // m_colorRange is still the Encoder base-class default (Limited)
+    // because PipeWireProduce::setupEncoder() calls setColorRange()
+    // AFTER the encoder is constructed. Building the filter string
+    // here would bake "out_range=limited" into the graph and silently
+    // ignore a later Full setting -- producing Limited YUV with a Full
+    // VUI tag, which mstsc then renders verbatim (lifted blacks).
+    // Build the filter string in initialize() instead.
 }
 
 bool LibX264Encoder::initialize(const QSize &size)
 {
+    auto colorRange = m_colorRange == PipeWireBaseEncodedStream::ColorRange::Full ? u"full"_s : u"limited"_s;
+    m_filterGraphToParse = u"format=yuv420p,pad=ceil(iw/2)*2:ceil(ih/2)*2,scale=out_color_matrix=bt601:out_range=%1"_s.arg(colorRange);
+    qCWarning(PIPEWIRERECORD_LOGGING) << "CONSOLERDP-LIBX264-FILTER-GRAPH" << m_filterGraphToParse;
     createFilterGraph(size);
 
     auto codec = avcodec_find_encoder_by_name("libx264");
@@ -80,6 +85,20 @@ bool LibX264Encoder::initialize(const QSize &size)
         break;
     }
 
+    // Tag the H.264 stream with explicit VUI color metadata so mstsc
+    // (and any other player) decodes YUV->RGB with the correct matrix
+    // and range, instead of guessing. Without these four fields set,
+    // libx264 writes color_description_present_flag=0 and mstsc defaults
+    // to BT.601 -- causing the washed-out / wrong-color look on a modern
+    // HD desktop, which is sRGB / BT.709 gamma-encoded. Set BT.601 for
+    // RDP-EGFX and obey the user's requested YUV range.
+    m_avCodecContext->color_range     = (m_colorRange == PipeWireBaseEncodedStream::ColorRange::Full)
+                                           ? AVCOL_RANGE_JPEG : AVCOL_RANGE_MPEG;
+    m_avCodecContext->color_primaries = AVCOL_PRI_SMPTE170M;
+    m_avCodecContext->color_trc       = AVCOL_TRC_SMPTE170M;
+    m_avCodecContext->colorspace      = AVCOL_SPC_SMPTE170M;
+    qCWarning(PIPEWIRERECORD_LOGGING) << "CONSOLERDP-BT601-VUI-PATCH-ACTIVE";
+
     AVDictionary *options = buildEncodingOptions();
     maybeLogOptions(options);
 
